Return the mean of array elements along a given axis. 

JAX implementation of [ ` numpy.mean()  ` ](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.mean.html#numpy.mean "\(in NumPy v2.2\)") . 

Parameters  : 
    

  * <::marker>

**a** ( _ArrayLike_ ) â€“ input array. 

  * <::marker>

**axis** ( _Axis_ _|_ _None_ ) â€“ optional, int or sequence of ints, default=None. Axis along which the mean to be computed. If None, mean is computed along all the axes. 

  * <::marker>

**dtype** ( _DTypeLike_ _|_ _None_ _|_ _None_ ) â€“ The type of the output array. If None (default) then the output dtype will be match the input dtype for floating point inputs, or be set to float32 or float64 for non-floating-point inputs. 

  * <::marker>

**keepdims** ( [ _bool_ ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#bool "\(in Python v3.13\)") ) â€“ bool, default=False. If true, reduced axes are left in the result with size 1. 

  * <::marker>

**where** ( _ArrayLike_ _|_ _None_ _|_ _None_ ) â€“ optional, boolean array, default=None. The elements to be used in the mean. Array should be broadcast compatible to the input. 

  * <::marker>

**out** ( _None_ _|_ _None_ ) â€“ Unused by JAX. 



Returns  : 
    

An array of the mean along the given axis.

[ Array ](jax.Array.html#jax.Array "jax.Array")

Notes 

For inputs of type  float16  or  bfloat16  , the reductions will be performed at float32 precision.

By default, the mean is computed along all the axes. 
    
    
    >>> x = jnp.array([[1, 3, 4, 2],
    ...                [5, 2, 6, 3],
